Moving from “avoiding repetition” to reducing cognitive load and architecture.
As I continue studying software engineering fundamentals, today’s lesson focused on one of the most common concepts in programming: functions.
At first, I saw functions mainly as a way to avoid repeating code. For example, if you have this logic:
Typescript:
const total = price * quantity;
const tax = total * 0.1;
const finalPrice = total + tax;If that same logic is needed in multiple places, wrapping it inside a function makes total sense:
function calculateFinalPrice(price: number, quantity: number): number {
const total = price * quantity;
const tax = total * 0.1;
return total + tax;
}While that is a valid use case, I realized functions provide much more value than simple code reuse.
Functions Help Organize Thinking
One idea that stood out to me is that functions help break down complex problems into smaller, more manageable pieces. Instead of having a single, massive block of code responsible for multiple tasks, we can separate each responsibility into its own dedicated function.
Consider this example:
Typescript:
function processOrder(order: Order) {
validateOrder(order);
saveOrder(order);
sendConfirmationEmail(order);
generateInvoice(order);
}Even without seeing the implementation details of each step, it’s instantly easy to understand what happens during the order lifecycle. The function names communicate intent.
Readability Matters
One lesson that keeps appearing throughout my studies is that we spend far more time reading code than writing it. Well-named functions can make our codebase feel much closer to the language of the business domain.
Compare these two ways of handling the same action:
Typescript:
// Vague and unclear
execute(order);// Clear and explicit
sendConfirmationEmail(order);
The second version immediately tells us what is happening under the hood. Small improvements like this have a massive impact on maintainability over time.
My Main Takeaway
Before this lesson, I mostly associated functions with reusability. Now, I’m starting to see them as a tool for:

• Separating responsibilities

• Improving readability

• Making code easier to test

• Reducing cognitive complexity

• Creating more maintainable systems
The more I study the fundamentals, the more I realize that good software engineering is often about small decisions repeated consistently.
